targetdoc="../elements/structural/note.xml" targetptr="note"><code>&lt;note&gt;</code></olink>,



<!-- modules not allowed in segment
<olink
targetdoc="../elements/structural/source.xml" targetptr="source"
><code>&lt;source&gt;</code></olink>, <olink targetdoc="../elements/structural/target.xml"
targetptr="target"><code>&lt;target&gt;</code></olink>,

-->

<olink targetdoc="../elements/inline/sc.xml"
targetptr="sc"><code>&lt;sc&gt;</code></olink>, <olink targetdoc="../elements/inline/ec.xml"
targetptr="ec"><code>&lt;ec&gt;</code></olink>, <olink targetdoc="../elements/inline/ph.xml"
targetptr="ph"><code>&lt;ph&gt;</code></olink>, <olink targetdoc="../elements/inline/pc.xml"
targetptr="pc"><code>&lt;pc&gt;</code></olink>, <olink targetdoc="../elements/inline/mrk.xml"
targetptr="mrk"><code>&lt;mrk&gt;</code></olink>, and  <olink targetdoc="../elements/inline/sm.xml"
targetptr="sm"><code>&lt;sm&gt;</code></olink>. </para>

<warning><para>The <link linkend="fs"><code>fs</code></link> attribute is not intended to facilitate <firstterm>Merging</firstterm> back into the original format. </para></warning>

<itemizedlist>
<title>Constraints</title>
<listitem><para>The <link linkend="fs"><code>fs</code></link> <glossterm>must</glossterm> only be used with <olink targetdoc="../elements/inline/ec.xml"
targetptr="ec"><code>&lt;ec&gt;</code></olink> in cases where the <code>isolated</code> attribute is set to 'yes'.</para>
</listitem>

</itemizedlist>


<itemizedlist>
<title>Processing Requirements</title>
<listitem>
<para><firstterm>Writers</firstterm> updating the attribute <link
 linkend="fs"><code>fs</code></link> <glossterm>must</glossterm> also update or delete <olink targetdoc="subFs.xml" targetptr="subFs"><code>subFs</code></olink>.</para>
</listitem>
</itemizedlist>

<para><emphasis>Example: </emphasis>To facilitate HTML preview, <link linkend="fs">fs</link> can be applied to XLIFF like this like:</para>
<!-- seems like a stray
<programlisting>&lt;ph id="ph1" fs:fs="img" fs:subFs="src,smileface.png" /></programlisting>
-->

<programlisting>
&lt;xliff xmlns:fs="urn:oasis:names:tc:xliff:fs:2.0"&gt;
  &lt;file fs:fs="html"&gt;
    &lt;unit id="1" fs:fs="p"&gt;
      &lt;segment&gt;
        &lt;source&gt;Mick Jones renewed his interest in the Vintage &lt;pc id="1"
            fs:fs="strong"&gt;'72 Telecaster Thinline &lt;/pc&gt; guitar.
            &lt;ph id="ph2" fs:fs="br" /&gt;He says &lt;pc fs:fs="q"&gt;I love 'em
            &lt;/pc&gt;&lt;ph id="ph1" fs:fs="img"
            fs:subFs="src,smileface.png" /&gt;&lt;/source&gt;
      &lt;/segment&gt;
    &lt;/unit&gt;
  &lt;/file&gt;
&lt;/xliff&gt;
</programlisting>


<para>With an XSL stylesheet like this: </para>

<programlisting>
&lt;xsl:template match="*" priority="2"
    xmlns:fs="urn:oasis:names:tc:xliff:fs:2.0">
  &lt;xsl:choose>
    &lt;xsl:when test="@fs:fs">
      &lt;xsl:element name="{@fs:fs}">
        &lt;xsl:if test="@fs:subFs">
          &lt;xsl:variable name="att_name"
              select="substring-before(@fs:subFs,',')" />
          &lt;xsl:variable name="att_val"
              select="substring-after(@fs:subFs,',')" />
          &lt;xsl:attribute name="{$att_name}">
            &lt;xsl:value-of select="$att_val" />
          &lt;/xsl:attribute>
        &lt;/xsl:if>
        &lt;xsl:apply-templates />
      &lt;/xsl:element>
    &lt;/xsl:when>
    &lt;xsl:otherwise>
      &lt;xsl:apply-templates />
    &lt;/xsl:otherwise>
  &lt;/xsl:choose>
&lt;/xsl:template>
</programlisting>

<para>You can generate a an HTML page like this: </para>

<programlisting>
&lt;html>
  &lt;p>Mick Jones renewed his interest in the Vintage &lt;strong>'72
      Telecaster Thinline &lt;/strong> guitar. &lt;br/>He says &lt;q>I love 'em
      &lt;/q>&lt;img src="smileface.png"/>&lt;/p>
&lt;/html>
</programlisting>

<!-- move to subFS
<para>For complex HTML previews that require more than one attribute on an HTML preview element, attribute pairs are separated by backslashes (\). Any literal comma or backslash in an attribute value <glossterm>must</glossterm> be escaped with a backslash.</para>

<para>For example, we would use this convention:</para>

<programlisting>&lt;ph id=”p1” fs=”img” subFs=”src,c:\\docs\\images\\smile.png\alt,My Happy Smile\title,Smiling faces\, are nice” /></programlisting>

<para>To produce this HTML preview:</para>

<programlisting>&lt;img src=”c:\docs\images\smile.png” alt=”My Happy Smile” title=”Smiling faces, are nice” /></programlisting>
-->
